<HEADLINE>
Subtle form of bait and switch?
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<POST>
<POSTER> Dave </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2005-07-09T06:19:00 </POSTDATE>
Email: &quot;Dave&quot;&lt;nofreekn ... @uhuh.uhh&gt;
Groups: misc.consumers


Over many years now, I've been complaining about how frustrating it is to
try to buy ANYTHING I want in a retail store. Most of the time, I find
whatever I'm looking for is sold out, or they don't carry it. I may be
slow, but I finally noticed a pattern. It goes like this. I've done my
research carefully to figure out what I want to buy. I want widget X. I
pull up the web sites of various stores like CompUSA, Best Buy, Circuit
City, etc. and see who carries it. Now I really want widget X quickly, so I
go to the local store to buy it. When I get there, widget X is sold out, or
&quot;Internet Only&quot; (when the web site doesn't specify &quot;Internet Only&quot;). But
they have gobs of widget Y on hand. Widget Y is invariably less useful
(worse specifications) AND a lot more expensive than widget X.

Now I'm living in an area where all the decent stores are a one hour drive
(one way) from home. And have you noticed the price of gas lately? So I'm
using the cell phone (free) to call ahead. Wouldn't you know it. I don't
even have to go to the store to get the bait and switch pitch. I called CC
to ask about a particular DVD recorder. It is listed on the CC web site.
No, it's not listed as Internet ONLY. But the salesman at CC told me that
it is Internet ONLY. Oh, but they have another brand that is less useful
for an extra hundred bucks, and they have plenty of THOSE in stock. How
helpful.

Now I don't mean to pick on Circuit City in particular. I generally like
them. But they are just the latest store that I've noticed is running this
particular scam. I think some stores (not just CC and BB) deliberately list
very good deals on their web site that are &quot;Internet ONLY&quot;, but not LABELLED
as such on the web site, just to get you into the retail store to buy
something at a much higher profit margin. Or, bait and switch.

Anybody else notice this? I think that there should be a law stating that
if you offer something for sale on your web site, then you must carry it in
your retail store, AND that you must make reasonable efforts to have it IN
STOCK, usually. -Dave

