"/> Don't listen to the high school kids who work at big box retailers.
They're more interested in avoiding work than they are in helping you
out.

I've related the story in the past of how I went to my local CompUSA
to pick up a laptop bag that the CompUSA web site listed as being in
stock at that store. There were none out on display, so I grabbed a
clerk and asked him to help me find them. He took a quick look on the
same shelves I had been looking at and said &quot;I've never seen that one
- we don't carry it.&quot; I pulled out my printout from the CompUSA web
site, proving that they DO carry it. His next lie was &quot;well, then,
we're out of stock.&quot; I pointed to the spot on the printout where it
said that his store had them in stock. His response: &quot;well, the web
site is wrong.&quot; I suggested that he check his own computer just to be
sure. He couldn't think of a reason not to, so he did (while I watched
over his shoulder to make sure he didn't lie and say they had none).
Sure enough, the computer showed 20 of them in stock. So he grudgingly
went back to the &quot;warehouse&quot; to look for one.

After about 5 mninutes he returned empty-handed, claiming he couldn't
find any. I asked if perhaps there was a MANAGER available who might
know where to find them. Realizing he wasn't going to get rid of me,
he once again disappeared into the &quot;warehouse,&quot; only this time he
returned with one of the laptop bags. Yes, just one - apparently he
wasn't interested in bringing out a few more to put out on the shelf
so maybe they could sell some.

To this day I have never seen a single one of those bags out on the
shelf (and I make it a point to look every time I go in, just to
check).

The moral of this story is you should never take a big box clerk's
word for it - especially if the web site shows the item in stock.
Escalate it to the manager if you have to - even if these kids aren't
motivated to sell you something, the manager sure ought to be.

